<h2 class="mw-headline" id="Overview">Overview</h2>
<p>The following diagram illustrates the architecture of this monitoring solution.<br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="SMA 2019.05 monitoring.png" src="/mediawiki/images/f/f7/SMA_2019.05_monitoring.png" width="960" height="547" data-file-width="960" data-file-height="547"></a><br>
</p>
<h3 class="mw-headline" id="Grafana">Grafana</h3>
<p>Grafana is a well-known dashboarding solution. It can create and manage separate dashboard access for different users and teams. In addition, Grafana uses the concept of “organizations” for multi- tenancy, which enables you to group resources and give access privileges to particular users.
</p><p>Grafana provides many plug-ins for different data sources such as InfluxDB, Graphite, Elasticsearch, and Prometheus. Using Grafana, you can create custom visualization panels that include graphs, tables, and lists based on queries against a particular data source. You can also query different data sources from the same dashboard, since each “panel” has a settings-like query, alert thresholds, and data source - all of which are easily configurable through the Grafana web UI.
</p>
<h3 class="mw-headline" id="Prometheus">Prometheus</h3>
<p>Prometheus is an open-source system monitoring and alerting toolkit originally built at SoundCloud. Prometheus's main features are:
</p>
<ul><li>A multi-dimensional data model with time series data identified by metric name and key/value pairs</li>
<li>A flexible query language to leverage this dimensionality</li>
<li>No reliance on distributed storage; single server nodes are autonomous</li>
<li>Time series collection happens via a pull model over HTTP</li>
<li>Pushing time series is supported via an intermediary gateway</li>
<li>Targets are discovered via service discovery or static configuration</li>
<li>Multiple modes of graphing and dashboarding support</li></ul>
<h2 class="mw-headline" id="Install_Prometheus">Install Prometheus</h2>
<p>Follow the instructions provided <a target="1" rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://marketplace.microfocus.com/itom/content/monitoring-pack">here</a> to install Prometheus.
</p>
<h2 class="mw-headline" id="Use_Prometheus">Use Prometheus</h2>
<h3 class="mw-headline" id="Access_the_Grafana_homepage">Access the Grafana homepage</h3>
<p>In a web browser, go to  https://&lt;external_access_host&gt;:9069 to enter the Grafana homepage. The default user name and password are admin/admin. You can change the password or add some other users on the privilege management page. 
</p><p>There are three dashboards available on the Micro Focus Marketplace website:&nbsp;
<a target="1" rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="https://marketplace.microfocus.com/itom/content/service-management-automation-diagnostic-toolkit">https://marketplace.microfocus.com/itom/content/service-management-automation-diagnostic-toolkit</a>
</p>
<h3 class="mw-headline" id="Dashboard-1:_General-os-metrics">Dashboard-1: General-os-metrics</h3>
<p>Lists OS level metrics such as CPU core, Memory, CPU usage, CPU iowait, Memory usage, system load, disk IOPS.<br>
<b>User case 1</b>: As a Cluster Admin, I want to know if all pods are running with resources balanced across all worker nodes.<br>
<b>Solution</b>: go to  1. General OS metrics and check the CPE and Memory usage for each worker node. Below are screenshots for a running system for worker nodes.<br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case1-1.1.png" src="/mediawiki/images/7/73/case1-1.1.png" width="1233" height="183" data-file-width="1233" data-file-height="183"></a> <br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case1-1.2.png" src="/mediawiki/images/c/c1/case1-1.2.png" width="1228" height="170" data-file-width="1228" data-file-height="170"></a> <br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case1-1.3.png" src="/mediawiki/images/6/65/case1-1.3.png" width="1231" height="171" data-file-width="1231" data-file-height="171"></a><br>
Comparing the 'Mem Usage' dashboard, we can see it's not balanced: 64%, 22% and 81%. The Admin is recommended to run the command below to re-balance the system.<br>
</p>
<pre>export namespace=`kubectl get namespace |grep itsma | cut -f1 -d " "`
kubectl patch deploy/itom-xruntime-platform -n $namespace -p '{"spec":{"template":{"spec":{"containers":[{"name":"itom-xruntime-platform","env":
[{"name":"RESTART_","value":"'$(date +%s)'"}]}]}}}}' kubectl patch deploy/itom-xruntime-gateway -n $namespace -p '{"spec":{"template":{"spec":{"containers":[{"name":"gateway","env":[{"name":"RESTART_","value":"'$(date +%s)'"}]}]}}}}'
kubectl patch deploy/itom-xruntime-serviceportal -n $namespace -p '{"spec":{"template":{"spec":{"containers":[{"name":"itom-xruntime-serviceportal","env":
</pre>
<p><a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case1-2.1.png" src="/mediawiki/images/0/04/case1-2.1.png" width="1243" height="169" data-file-width="1243" data-file-height="169"></a> <br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case1-2.2.png" src="/mediawiki/images/8/87/case1-2.2.png" width="1233" height="171" data-file-width="1233" data-file-height="171"></a><br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case1-2.3.png" src="/mediawiki/images/7/71/case1-2.3.png" width="1231" height="170" data-file-width="1231" data-file-height="170"></a><br>
<b>User case 2</b>: As a Cluster admin, I want to know the system load in the pas 3 hours. <br>
<b>Solution</b>: go to  1. General OS metrics and check dashboard 'System Load', click Text 'System Load' and choose 'View' from the drop down list.<br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case2.png" src="/mediawiki/images/5/5c/case2.png" width="1343" height="414" data-file-width="1343" data-file-height="414"></a><br>
</p>
<h3 class="mw-headline" id="Dashboard-2:_Kubernetes-cluster-metrics">Dashboard-2: Kubernetes-cluster-metrics</h3>
<p>Provides information about the Kubernetes cluster system, including system running time, pod available status, cpu/memory/network usage for individual pods.<br>
<b>User case 3</b>: As a Cluster Admin, I want to know system status in past 3 hours, if there is any abnormal pods. 
<b>Solution</b>: Go to 2. Kubernetes cluster metrics, then check 'Unavailable Replicas' and 'Unavailable Pods' dashboard'. <br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case3.png" src="/mediawiki/images/3/36/case3.png" width="1072" height="262" data-file-width="1072" data-file-height="262"></a><br>
Explanation: Above dash board shows that currently, there are two pods are not available, means there maybe something wrong with this cluster, and in 2017-07-26 13:57:45, itom-xruntime-platform and itom-xruntime-platform-offline is not ready.<br>
Change time serial to a smaller one then the dashboard is more clear.<br>
<b>User Case 4</b>: As a Cluster Admin, I want to know some pod's CPU and Memory usage, to monitor the usage and trend, for example, itom-xruntime-platform.<br>
<b>Solution</b>: Go to  Go to 2. Kubernetes cluster metrics, filter Deployment by key works 'platform' and choose 'itom-xruntime-platform'.<br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="case4.png" src="/mediawiki/images/9/90/case4.png" width="1839" height="706" data-file-width="1839" data-file-height="706"></a> <br>
Explanation: in this dashboard, we can see that platform pod memory is increasing from 470 MB and reach to 3.7 GB in 10 minutes and then it's stable.<br>
</p>
<h3 class="mw-headline" id="Dashboard-3:_Kubernetes-pods">Dashboard-3: Kubernetes-pods</h3>
<p>Provides Kubernetes pod information, such as CPU/Memory/Network RX/Network TX usage. <br>
<a onclick="javascript:loadingImage(this);" class="image"><img alt="SMA 2019.05 monitoring dashboard3.png" src="/mediawiki/images/d/d2/SMA_2019.05_monitoring_dashboard3.png" width="1376" height="671" data-file-width="1376" data-file-height="671"></a> <br>
</p>



